issue_comment_body:
For what it's worth, I fixed this on the call site as follows:

First start training as usual, but create a `future` on the result:

    using namespace std:
    future<net_type> f = async(launch::async, [&my_trainer]() { return my_trainer.get_net(); });

Then later check if the training is ready as follows (and if not, then just keep using an earlier `my_processing_net`):

    if (f.wait_for(chrono::seconds(0)) == future_status::ready) {
        my_processing_net = f.get();
    }

(Note that `my_trainer` doesn't train `my_processing_net` directly, but another net, which is not shown above.)

The `wait_for(seconds(0)) == ready` is essentially the `!is_training()` that I was looking for.

I think this pretty much does what I wanted in the first place: I never need to block where `my_processing_net` is used, yet I get the new training result in use there without unnecessary delay. Moreover, there's not too much thread-related boilerplate: my main loop just receives new data, initiates a new training iteration if enough new data has been accumulated for a minibatch or so (the training of course goes to a separate thread, which dlib makes very clean), checks if there's a new training result available and updates `my_processing_net` if so (this is the second snippet above), and finally uses `my_processing_net` to process the new data (not shown above).

@davisking I'm sorry but i could not invest as much time as i wished to. I committed and pushed my change into my `merge_pybind_build` branch. Basically I went through all the initialization you were doing before the `add_python_module` definition and checked whether `pybind11_add_module` did that already. If not (most cases), i copied it into the `CMakeLists.txt` of the python module.

I also left the `PYTHON3` option in the meantime, but only for the executable lookup. The selection-setup of python versions is left to the pybind11 build process. The executable lookup is something that probably also should be changed... if most people use `setup.py` as their build-process anyway then simply passing `sys.executable` to the cmake-build is much more robust than trying to guess this yourself in cmake. For instance if you create a virtualenv with python3 in order to setup dlib there, by default the python executable on the path will be `python` and not `python3`.

I tested it with both `setup.py` and individual cmake builds for python 2.7 and 3.6 under linux... successfully. Under windows i still get an empty `DLIB_VERSION` which is curious but did not have the time to investigate further. If you can wait another day, i will have a go at that.

@timotheecour , do you have CUDNN 5.0 installed? CUDNN != CUDA
Also if you have CUDNN 4 installed and CUDNN 5 both installed on the same system - you can get this problem, if CUDNN4 is installed (or may be restored somehow) after CUDNN5 - it rewrites headers and library files

Try unpack CUDNN 5 in some folder and put it as param to -DCMAKE_PREFIX_PATH when building dlib

