From what I understand, django adds new entries to the `django_migrations` table when you apply a migration that replaces a previous one. So, assuming that you applied all previous migrations (which you did if you just upgraded from python-social-auth to the new social-auth-core), simply add the missing migration rows manually like this:
```sql
INSERT INTO `django_migrations` (`app`, `name`, `applied`) VALUES ("social_auth", "0001_initial", NOW());
INSERT INTO `django_migrations` (`app`, `name`, `applied`) VALUES ("social_auth", "0003_alter_email_max_length", NOW());
INSERT INTO `django_migrations` (`app`, `name`, `applied`) VALUES ("social_auth", "0004_auto_20160423_0400", NOW());
INSERT INTO `django_migrations` (`app`, `name`, `applied`) VALUES ("social_auth", "0002_add_related_name", NOW());```
```

@drachenminister is correct, the issue was fixed in 8c9c32f9a72b0e49e67e4e5bd7cfcb3565c87597. However, the last release (v0.2) predates this fix, which is why you are experiencing the bug if you are installing from Pypi (for example using `pip install`). You can either:
- install directly from git
- wait until I release v0.3 with the latext fixes on Pypi. This should be sometime next week;  after that `pip install --upragde` should solve your problem.

