@pfreixes 
1. Yes, from my understanding context manager should close connection on exception
2. `release` returns a connection back to pool. If exception has occurred the connection is in undefined state: it can have not-read-yet data etc. Dropping the connection entirely by `close()` is safer.

I suspect it's related to the fact that any errors in *handlers* for an event are raised in the `.trigger` call. For instance, in:

```javascript
        events.one('test_event', function () {
            console.log('triggered');
            undefined_error();
        })
        console.log('triggering');
        events.trigger('test_event');
        console.log('after trigger');
```

`after trigger` will never be reached due to the error in the event handler raising in the `.trigger()` call. So any error in an event handler called during the notebook-loading path can preempt setting the finished-loading flag.

